    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1893-11-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1893-11-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="470"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d470">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Señor <persName
                            type="to">Romero</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1893-11-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 28, 1893</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to say in further reference to your note
                    of the 17th instant, that, as I learn by a telegram of 24th instant referred to
                    me by the Secretary of War on the 25th, the commanding officer of the troops at
                    San Antonio, Tex., is “of opinion that no armed party has crossed into Mexico
                    from the United States at any point in the vicinity of El Paso,” and adds that
                    “Col. Lazelle is now in control of matters at that point, from whom a report is
                    expected very soon as to the expediency of returning the cavalry to its
                    post.”</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin E. Uhl</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
